PART 1 — Create a VPC

Search VPC in AWS search bar
Click Create VPC
Two approaches seen in the docs:

Method A (VPC only — used cin Practical 4 TYBVOC version):

Resources to create → VPC only
Name tag → my-vpc-prac
IPv4 CIDR → 10.0.0.0/16
IPv6 → No IPv6
Tenancy → Default
Click Create VPC

Method B (VPC and more — used in Practical 4 original version):

Resources to create → VPC and more
Name → prac4 (auto-generates everything)
IPv4 CIDR → 10.0.0.0/16
Number of AZs → 2
Public subnets → 1, Private subnets → 1
NAT Gateways → None (for now)
Click Create VPC

Exam tip: If asked just to "create a VPC," go with VPC only, set name and CIDR 10.0.0.0/16, click create.

PART 2 — Create Public & Private Subnets
(Only needed if you used VPC only method)
Create Public Subnet:

Go to VPC → Subnets → Create subnet
VPC ID → select your VPC (my-vpc-prac)
Subnet name → my-subnet-public-1
Availability Zone → ap-south-1a
IPv4 CIDR → 10.0.0.0/24
Click Create subnet

Create Private Subnet:

Same steps, but:
Subnet name → my-subnet-private-1
IPv4 CIDR → 10.0.1.0/24
Click Create subnet

PART 3 — Create Public & Private Route Tables

Go to VPC → Route tables → Create route table

Public Route Table:

Name → my-rt-public
VPC → select your VPC
Click Create route table

Private Route Table:

Name → my-rt-private
VPC → select your VPC
Click Create route table

PART 4 — Route Table to Subnet Association
Associate public subnet to public route table:

In Route tables, right-click my-rt-public → Edit subnet associations
Check my-subnet-public-1
Click Save associations

Associate private subnet to private route table:

Right-click my-rt-private → Edit subnet associations
Check my-subnet-private-1
Click Save associations

PART 5 — Create Internet Gateway & Attach to VPC

Go to VPC → Internet gateways → Create internet gateway
Name → my-internet-gtw
Click Create internet gateway
After creation, click Attach to a VPC (green banner at top)
Select your VPC → Click Attach internet gateway

PART 6 — Create NAT Gateway

Go to VPC → NAT gateways → Create NAT gateway
Name → my-nat-gateway
Subnet → select your public subnet (NAT goes in public!)
Connectivity type → Public
Elastic IP → Click Allocate Elastic IP
Click Create NAT gateway

Important: NAT Gateway is placed in the Public Subnet, not private.

PART 7 — Update Route Tables
Public Route Table → Add Internet Gateway route:

Select my-rt-public → Routes tab → Edit routes
Click Add route
Destination → 0.0.0.0/0
Target → Internet Gateway → select your IGW
Click Save changes

Private Route Table → Add NAT Gateway route:

Select my-rt-private → Routes tab → Edit routes
Click Add route
Destination → 0.0.0.0/0
Target → NAT Gateway → select your NAT GW
Click Save changes

PART 8 — Create Security Groups
Public Security Group:

Go to VPC → Security groups → Create security group
Name → public-sg
Description → Allow SSH access to developer
VPC → your VPC
Inbound rules → Add rule: Type SSH, Port 22, Source Anywhere (or your local IP /32)
Click Create security group

Private Security Group:

Same steps, Name → private-sg
Inbound rules → Type SSH, Port 22, Source → public subnet CIDR 10.0.0.0/24
Click Create security group

PART 9 — Create Key Pair

Go to EC2 → Key Pairs → Create key pair
Name → vpc-kp
Key pair type → RSA
Private key format → .pem (for OpenSSH/Mac/Linux) or .ppk (for PuTTY/Windows)
Click Create key pair — file downloads automatically

PART 10 — Create IAM Role

Search IAM → Roles → Create role
Trusted entity type → AWS service
Use case → S3
Next → Add permissions → search AmazonS3FullAccess → check it
Role name → S3_full_access
Click Create role

PART 11 — Launch EC2 Instances
Public EC2:

Go to EC2 → Instances → Launch instances
Name → ubuntu-public
AMI → Ubuntu Server 22.04 LTS
Instance type → t2.micro (free tier)
Key pair → select vpc-kp
Network settings → Edit:

VPC → your VPC
Subnet → my-subnet-public-1
Auto-assign public IP → Enable
Security group → select public-sg

Click Launch instance

Private EC2:

Same steps, Name → ubuntu-private
Network settings:

Subnet → my-subnet-private-1
Auto-assign public IP → Disable
Security group → select private-sg

Click Launch instance

PART 12 — Add Inbound Rules to Security Groups
(If not done during creation)
Public SG — Allow SSH from your local IP:

EC2 → Security Groups → select public-sg
Inbound rules → Edit inbound rules
Add rule: SSH, TCP, port 22, Source → My IP (auto-fills your IP)
Save rules

Private SG — Allow SSH from public subnet:

Select private-sg → Edit inbound rules
Add rule: SSH, TCP, port 22, Source → 10.0.0.0/24 (public subnet CIDR)
Save rules

