PART 13 — The "Bastion" Connection (SSH Agent Forwarding)
On your local machine (Mac/Linux):

ssh-add vpc-kp.pem
ssh -A ubuntu@<Public-IP-of-Public-EC2>

On your local machine (Windows/PuTTY):
Enable "Allow agent forwarding" in the Connection -> SSH -> Auth settings.

Once inside the Public EC2:
Simply run: ssh ubuntu@10.0.1.x (the private IP of your Private EC2).

PART 14 — Attach the IAM Role to the Instance
In Part 10, you created an IAM Role, but you didn't attach it to the EC2 instance yet.

Go to EC2 Instances.
Select your Private EC2 instance.
Click Actions → Security → Modify IAM role.
Select S3_full_access and click Update IAM role.

Why? This allows your private instance to talk to S3 without needing to store secret access keys on the server.

#extra run ------
Step 1: On your Local Computer (Terminal/PowerShell)
Connect to your Public EC2 (The Bastion Host).

Bash
ssh -i "vpc-kp.pem" ubuntu@<PUBLIC_IP_OF_PUBLIC_EC2>
Once this succeeds, your terminal prompt will change to something like ubuntu@ip-10-0-0-x:~$.

Step 2: From the Public EC2 (The "Bridge")
Now, inside that terminal, connect to your Private EC2 using its Private IP.

Bash
ssh ubuntu@10.0.1.x
(Note: For this to work without copying keys, refer to the "SSH Agent Forwarding" tip in the previous step, or temporarily paste your private key content into a file on the Public EC2).

Step 3: Inside the Private EC2 (The "Destination")
This is where you run your verification commands. Once your prompt shows the private IP (e.g., ubuntu@ip-10-0-1-x:~$), run these:

1. Test the NAT Gateway (Internet Access)
   Bash
   ping -c 4 google.com
   What to look for: If you see "64 bytes from...", the NAT Gateway and Route Tables are perfectly configured.

If it fails: Check if your Private Route Table has a route to 0.0.0.0/0 pointing to the NAT Gateway.

2. Test the IAM Role (S3 Access)
   First, update your package list and install the AWS tool:

Bash
sudo apt update && sudo apt install awscli -y
aws s3 ls
What to look for: A list of your S3 buckets (or a blank line if you have no buckets).

If it fails: Ensure the IAM Role was attached to the Private EC2 instance in the Console.

3. Test Internal Connectivity
   Bash
   ping -c 4 <PRIVATE_IP_OF_PUBLIC_EC2>
   What to look for: Success proves the instances can talk to each other over the local 10.0.0.0/16 network.

